uthors shake off the shackles of the orientalist legacy but retain a close reading of local processes. They challenge the boundaries of China and question its study from different perspectives, but believe that area studies have a role to play if their geographies are studied according to certain common problems.In the case of China, the book shows the diverse array of critical but solidly grounded research approaches that can be used in studying a society. Its approach neither trivializes nor dismisses the elusive effects of culture, and it pays attention to both the state and the multiplicity of voices that challenge it.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aNationalismxChina. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Ideologies / Nationalism & Patriotism.2bisacsh  a21st century, China, Empires, Foreign relations, Modernity, Nationalism, Racism Russia.1 aBreidenbach, Joana, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDikötter, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDuara, Prasenjit, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdwards, Penny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGladney, Dru C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLomanov, Alexander V., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMarcus, George E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNyiri, Pál, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNyíri, Pál, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOng, Aihwa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchein, Louisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZha, Daojiong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato